---
import { mobileData, wealthDistributionData } from "../../data/charts";
import { wealthSection } from "../../data/sections";
import CiteButton from "../CiteButton.astro";
import BarChart from "../charts/BarChart.astro";
import GiniChart from "../charts/GiniChart.astro";
import HistoryChart from "../charts/HistoryChart.astro";
import PullQuote from "../PullQuote.astro";
import SourceList from "../SourceList.astro";
---

<section id="wealth" aria-labelledby="wealth-heading">
	<div class="section-label reveal-left">Wealth Inequality</div>
	<h2 id="wealth-heading" class="reveal" style="transition-delay: 0.1s">
		The Great<br />Upward<br />Transfer
	</h2>
	<p class="section-intro reveal" style="transition-delay: 0.2s">
		The post-war egalitarian era was not natural or inevitable — it was
		won through organised labour and political will. The neoliberal
		revolution, originating in the USA and exported globally through the
		IMF and World Bank, reversed those gains in a generation.
	</p>
	<figure class="chart-box reveal" style="transition-delay: 0.1s">
		<figcaption class="chart-title">
			Top 1% Income Share — USA, 1913–2025<CiteButton citation={wealthSection.chartCitations.history} />
		</figcaption>
		<div
			id="history-desktop-chart"
			class="desktop-chart"
			role="img"
			aria-label="Line chart showing top 1% income share in the USA from 1913 to 2025, peaking at 24% before the 1929 crash, falling to 10% by 1970, then rising back to 21% by 2025"
		>
			<HistoryChart />
		</div>
		<div id="history-mobile-chart" class="mobile-chart" role="img" aria-label="Bar chart showing top 1% income share in the USA at key historical points">
			<BarChart id="history-mobile-bars" items={mobileData.history} />
		</div>
		<table class="sr-only">
			<caption>Top 1% Income Share — USA, Key Years</caption>
			<thead><tr><th>Year</th><th>Share</th></tr></thead>
			<tbody>
				<tr><td>1913</td><td>18%</td></tr>
				<tr><td>1929</td><td>24%</td></tr>
				<tr><td>1945</td><td>13%</td></tr>
				<tr><td>1970</td><td>10%</td></tr>
				<tr><td>1980</td><td>11%</td></tr>
				<tr><td>2000</td><td>21%</td></tr>
				<tr><td>2007</td><td>24%</td></tr>
				<tr><td>2018</td><td>19%</td></tr>
				<tr><td>2023</td><td>21%</td></tr>
				<tr><td>2025</td><td>21%</td></tr>
			</tbody>
		</table>
	</figure>
	<SourceList items={wealthSection.sources} />
	<div class="two-col wealth-layout">
		<div class="col-text">
			<p>
				Since the 1980s, the share of wealth held by the bottom half of
				the global population has collapsed. Wage suppression,
				financialisation, and tax policy have systematically redirected
				economic output from workers to shareholders across every major
				economy. In South Africa — the world's most unequal major economy
				— decades of neoliberal policy have entrenched apartheid-era
				wealth concentration under democratic governance. The middle class
				is not "squeezed" — it is being liquidated.
			</p>
			<PullQuote data={wealthSection.pullQuote} />
			<SourceList items={[...wealthSection.sources, ...wealthSection.additionalSources]} />
		</div>
		<div class="col-charts">
			<figure class="chart-box reveal">
				<figcaption class="chart-title">
					US Wealth Distribution<CiteButton citation={wealthSection.chartCitations.distribution} />
				</figcaption>
				<div role="img" aria-label="Bar chart showing US wealth distribution: Top 1% owns 31%, Next 9% owns 37%, Next 40% owns 30%, Bottom 50% owns 2%">
					<BarChart id="wealth-distribution-chart" items={wealthDistributionData} outsideValueThreshold={5} />
				</div>
			</figure>
			<figure class="chart-box reveal" style="transition-delay: 0.12s">
				<figcaption class="chart-title">
					Wealth Gini Coefficient by Country
				</figcaption>
				<div
					id="gini-desktop-chart"
					class="desktop-chart"
					role="img"
					aria-label="Wealth Gini coefficients by country (Credit Suisse/UBS 2021): France 0.70, UK 0.71, Germany 0.79, USA 0.85, Sweden 0.88, South Africa 0.89, Brazil 0.89. Higher values indicate greater wealth inequality. USA and South Africa are highlighted as extreme cases."
				>
					<GiniChart />
				</div>
				<div id="gini-mobile-chart" class="mobile-chart" role="img" aria-label="Bar chart comparing wealth Gini coefficients across countries">
					<BarChart id="gini-mobile-bars" items={mobileData.gini} />
				</div>
				<table class="sr-only">
					<caption>Wealth Gini Coefficient by Country</caption>
					<thead><tr><th>Country</th><th>Gini</th></tr></thead>
					<tbody>
						<tr><td>Germany</td><td>0.67</td></tr>
						<tr><td>France</td><td>0.70</td></tr>
						<tr><td>Sweden</td><td>0.74</td></tr>
						<tr><td>Brazil</td><td>0.78</td></tr>
						<tr><td>UK</td><td>0.81</td></tr>
						<tr><td>USA</td><td>0.85</td></tr>
						<tr><td>South Africa</td><td>0.91</td></tr>
					</tbody>
				</table>
			</figure>
		</div>
	</div>
</section>
